11 Workshop GEE and GLMM

Xanthe Walker

2025-08-08

Introduction

Reminder on family in GLMs/GEEs: Setting a family picks a link and meanvariance relationship (e.g., Poisson: log link, Var=). Its a modeling framework for the mean; GEE then uses a working correlation structure for within-cluster correlation and robust (sandwich) SEs.

1. Generalized Estimating Equations

In this part, well fit Generalized Estimating Equations (GEE) to repeated count data. GEE is a great option when you:

  • have correlated observations (e.g., repeated measures within fields),

  • want population-averaged (marginal) effects rather than subject-specific effects, and

  • dont want to fully specify random effects or a full likelihood.

Well use time series of aquatic bird species richness recorded in California rice fields. Our questions:

  • Does richness vary with management type (flooding vs.not), water depth, and field size?

  • What correlation structure best reflects within-field temporal correlation (AR-1 vs exchangeable vs independence)?

  • How do results change across structures, and what does QIC say?

Load and restructure data

# Load data (adjust path if needed)
RFBirds <- read.csv("../../Data files/RiceFieldBirds.csv")

# Species richness across columns 8:56 (presence > 0) as given in notes
RFBirds$Richness <- rowSums(RFBirds[, 8:56] > 0)

# Factors and transforms
RFBirds$fField   <- factor(RFBirds$FIELD)
RFBirds$fSptreat <- factor(RFBirds$SPTREAT)   # management/flooding treatment
RFBirds$LA       <- log(RFBirds$AREA)         # log field area
RFBirds$DEPTH2   <- RFBirds$DEPTH^2           # optional nonlinearity

# Quick check
summary(RFBirds[, c("Richness", "DEPTH", "AREA")])

> Design: repeated measures within fields we must account for within-field correlation.

Fit a GEE

We start with a Poisson GEE for richness with a log link and cluster on fField. We include log area (LA), treatment, and depth. (You can test a curvature with DEPTH2.)

gee_ar1 <- geeglm(
  Richness ~ LA + fSptreat + DEPTH,
  id      = fField,
  data    = RFBirds,
  family  = poisson,
  corstr  = "ar1"   # AR(1): closer time points more correlated
)
summary(gee_ar1)

Why AR-1? Biological reasoning: counts in a field at time s likely depend on those at s1 (and less so on s2, ). This favors AR-1 over exchangeable (equal correlation for all lags) or independence. Unstructured is rarely practical with sparse time series per field.

Compare correlation structures

We refit the same mean model but vary the working correlation: AR-1, exchangeable, independence.

gee_exch <- geeglm(Richness ~ LA + fSptreat + DEPTH,
                   id = fField, data = RFBirds,
                   family = poisson, corstr = "exchangeable")

gee_ind  <- geeglm(Richness ~ LA + fSptreat + DEPTH,
                   id = fField, data = RFBirds,
                   family = poisson, corstr = "independence")

tab_model(gee_ar1, gee_exch, gee_ind)

You should see very similar coefficients and slightly different SEs across structures (GEE is robust to misspecified correlation for the mean estimates).

Compare with QIC

GEE doesnt provide AIC. Use QIC to compare working correlation structures for a given mean model.

# Compute/compare QIC
QIC(gee_ar1)
##       QIC      QICu Quasi Lik       CIC    params      QICC 
##   -486.95   -489.13    248.56      5.09      4.00   -474.95
QIC(gee_exch)
##       QIC      QICu Quasi Lik       CIC    params      QICC 
##  -487.115  -489.217   248.609     5.051     4.000  -475.115
QIC(gee_ind)
##       QIC      QICu Quasi Lik       CIC    params      QICC 
##  -487.022  -489.277   248.639     5.128     4.000  -480.355

QICs are identical or nearly so, pick the simplest (often independence) or the one best supported by biology (often AR-1 for time series).

Model Diagnostics

GEE diagnostics are more limited than GLM/GLMM. Theres no exact DHARMa equivalent for geeglm, and residuals can be hard to interpret. Still, some simple checks help:

  • Pearson residuals vs fitted (look for structure or extreme outliers)

  • QQ-plot of Pearson residuals (purely heuristic)

  • Within-cluster residual patterns over time

# Pearson residuals & fitted
fit_ar1 <- predict(gee_ar1, type = "response")
res_ar1 <- residuals(gee_ar1, type = "pearson")

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
plot(fit_ar1, res_ar1, pch = 16, cex = 0.7,
     xlab = "Fitted values", ylab = "Pearson residuals",
     main = "Residuals vs fitted (AR-1)")
abline(h = 0, lty = 2)
qqnorm(res_ar1, main = "QQ-plot (Pearson residuals)"); qqline(res_ar1)

par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

# Residuals over time within a couple of example fields
example_fields <- head(levels(RFBirds$fField), 6)
RFBirds$pearson_res <- res_ar1

xyplot(pearson_res ~ Time | fField, data = subset(RFBirds, fField %in% example_fields),
       type = c("p", "smooth"), layout = c(3, 2),
       ylab = "Pearson residuals", xlab = "Time")

These checks are heuristic. For binomial GEE, plots often look worse even for acceptable fits. Focus on gross deviations rather than perfect normality.

Optional refinements

Overdispersion: Poisson with robust SEs is typically fine under GEE, but if overdispersion is strong, consider adding predictors (e.g., DEPTH2) or switching to a quasi-Poisson GEE (family = quasipoisson) recognizing that QIC comparisons get tricky.

Offsets vs covariates: If you want a rate per area, use offset(LA) instead of LA as a covariate.

# Example with an offset for area (rate of richness per area unit)
gee_ar1_off <- geeglm(Richness ~ fSptreat + DEPTH,
                      offset = LA,
                      id = fField, data = RFBirds,
                      family = poisson, corstr = "ar1")
summary(gee_ar1_off)

Model selection and reduction

We will use a Wald tests via anova.geeglm to determine if reducing the model if justified.

gee_ar1 <- geeglm(
  Richness ~ LA + fSptreat + DEPTH,
  id      = fField,
  data    = RFBirds,
  family  = poisson,
  corstr  = "ar1"   # AR(1): closer time points more correlated
)

gee_ar1_B <- geeglm(
  Richness ~ LA + fSptreat,
  id      = fField,
  data    = RFBirds,
  family  = poisson,
  corstr  = "ar1"   # AR(1): closer time points more correlated
)

gee_ar1_C <- geeglm(
  Richness ~ LA + DEPTH,
  id      = fField,
  data    = RFBirds,
  family  = poisson,
  corstr  = "ar1"   # AR(1): closer time points more correlated
)

gee_ar1_D <- geeglm(
  Richness ~ fSptreat + DEPTH,
  id      = fField,
  data    = RFBirds,
  family  = poisson,
  corstr  = "ar1"   # AR(1): closer time points more correlated
)



anova(gee_ar1, gee_ar1_B)  # Wald test for dropping DEPTH

Interpreting coefficients

For a log link, exponentiate coefficients to get multiplicative effects on the expected mean richness. These are also provided with the tab_model function

exp(coef(gee_ar1_final))
## (Intercept)          LA 
##        1.73        1.62
tab_model(gee_ar1_final)
Richness
Predictors Incidence Rate Ratios CI p
(Intercept) 1.73 1.012.97 0.046
LA 1.62 1.322.00 <0.001
N fField 11
Observations 110

If exp(_DEPTH) = 1.62, then each 1-unit increase in LA is associated with a 62% increase in expected richness (marginal, population-averaged), holding other predictors constant.

Plot model results

plot(ggpredict(gee_ar1_final), show_data=TRUE)

Summary

  1. Start with a biologically motivated mean model and choose a working correlation consistent with your design (AR-1 for time series is common).

  2. Fit several structures (AR-1, exchangeable, independence) and compare with QIC.

  3. Use simple residual plots for sanity checks; dont over-interpret them.

  4. Report population-averaged effect sizes (e.g., exponentiated coefficients) and discuss robustness.

2. Generalized Linear Mixed Model (GLMM)

In this part, well model repeated count data with GLMMs using glmmTMB. Unlike GEE (population-averaged), GLMMs estimate subject-specific effects via random effects and a full likelihood.

Study context (Price et al.2016):

  • Stressors: Mountaintop removal mining with valley fill (MTR/VF) may impact stream ecosystems.

  • Organisms: Stream salamanders, which are sensitive to land-use change.

  • Design: Counts from 23 headwater streams (sites) 11 mined, 12 reference. Each stream was sampled 4 times (monthly MarchJune 2013). Salamanders were identified to species (and sometimes life stage).

  • Implication: Repeated measures within sites pseudo-replication if ignored. Well include a random intercept for site to account for within-site correlation.

Load and prepare the data

Use the Salamanders data from the glmmTMB package. Key variables well use:

  • count: salamander counts

  • spp: species (and/or life stage)

  • mined: factor indicating mined vs reference site

  • site: site ID (random-effect grouping)

  • sample: sampling occasion (time ordering within site)

# If not already loaded:
data("Salamanders", package = "glmmTMB")

# Peek

Fit a Poisson GLMM with a random intercept for site

Reading the output:

  • Random-effects block shows the variance and SD of the site intercepts (e.g., Var 0.33 SD 0.575).

  • Fixed-effects table shows log-scale coefficients and Wald tests. Wald p-values can be optimistic in small samples; prefer likelihood-based comparison (AIC/LRT) for selection.

  • For interpretation on the count scale, exponentiate coefficients for incidence rate ratios (IRRs) or look at the tab_model output.

Diagnostics with DHARMa

set.seed(1)
res_pois <- simulateResiduals(poisfit)
plot(res_pois)

check_overdispersion(res_pois)
## # Overdispersion test
## 
##  dispersion ratio = 1.540
##           p-value =  0.16

Dont over-interpret the formal DHARMa tests: with large n, tiny deviations become significant. Scan visually for gross patterns or outliers.

If Poisson is too narrow (variance mean), use Negative Binomial.

Dispersion models

We will fit a negative binomial model (nbinom2), which assumes the variance increases quadratically with the mean.

  family = nbinom2,
  data = Salamanders
)

You can let dispersion vary with covariates using dispformula (log link). This parallels variance functions in GLS. If counts were expected to become more dispersed (more variable relative to the mean) over the four months, then this can be included to model how the dispersion changes with the day of the year (DOY):

nbfit_disp <- glmmTMB(
  count ~ spp * mined + (1 | site),
  family = nbinom2,
  dispformula = ~ sample,   # example: allow dispersion to vary by time index
  data = Salamanders
)
AIC(nbfit1, nbfit_disp)
##            df  AIC
## nbfit1     16 1663
## nbfit_disp 17 1664

Model Selection

Two common routes (often agree):

  • drop1() to remove the highest-order interaction via LRT (on ML fits).

  • Fit nested candidates and compare by AIC and/or LRT.

# Drop the interaction from the NB model
nbfit_noint <- glmmTMB(count ~ spp + mined + (1 | site),
                       family = nbinom2, data = Salamanders)

AIC(nbfit1, nbfit_noint)

lrtest(nbfit1, nbfit_noint)

If the interaction is retained, interpretation must be interaction-aware (i.e., plot predicted means rather than isolate main effects).

Plot predictions

best_nb <- nbfit1

p_counts <- ggpredict(best_nb, terms = c("spp", "mined"))
plot(p_counts) + ggtitle("Predicted counts by species  mining status")

Interpretation: Mining reduces salamander counts across species, but the magnitude differs by species (visible as different gaps between mined vs reference within each spp).

Exercises

For both exercises that follow you will use the Owls data set (Owls.csv). These data come from a study of vocal begging behavior in owl nestlings.

Variables youll use:

  • NCalls: number of calls in 30 s before a parents arrival (response)

  • BroodSize: number of nestlings (use offset(log(BroodSize)))

  • SexParent: sex of visiting parent (factor)

  • FoodTreatment: Deprived vs Satiated

  • ArrivalTime: time within the night (numeric/continuous)

  • Nest: nest ID (cluster)

  • NestNight: grouping factor for same nest, same night, e.g.Nest.Dep vs Nest.Sat

# Load data
Owls <- read.csv("../../Data files/Owls.csv")

# Create variables used in the analysis
Owls$NCalls     <- Owls$SiblingNegotiation
Owls$LBroodSize <- log(Owls$BroodSize)
Owls$NestNight  <- factor(ifelse(Owls$FoodTreatment == "Deprived",
                                 paste(Owls$Nest, ".Dep", sep=""),
                                 paste(Owls$Nest, ".Sat", sep="")))

1. GEE (population-averaged)

  1. Plot the data. Make a quick visualization of NCalls vs ArrivalTime and a box/violin plot by FoodTreatment. Briefly describe patterns.

  2. Start with a Poisson GLM. Fit NCalls ~ offset(LBroodSize) + SexParentFoodTreatment + SexParentArrivalTime (family = Poisson). Comment on overdispersion using a dispersion statistic or residual plot.

  3. Refit with quasipoisson. Test whether each interaction is needed and simplify the model. Report the final formula.

  4. Fit GEE with cluster id = Nest and correlation = exchangeable. What is the estimated within-nest correlation? Is it plausible?

  5. Try AR(1). Fit GEE with cluster id = NestNight and corstr = ar1. Compare parameter estimates and SEs to the exchangeable model. Which feels more biologically reasonable here?

  6. Compare correlation structures with QIC. Use QIC to compare (a) exchangeable vs (b) AR(1). Which wins? Briefly justify.

  7. Starting from the AR(1) model, test the two interactions (Wald tests via anova.geeglm). Reduce to a main-effects model if justified.

  8. Interpretation. From your final GEE: interpret the effect of FoodTreatment and ArrivalTime on NCalls. Plot the predicted relationships.

2. GLMM (subject-specific)

  1. Fit a random-intercept GLMM with NCalls ~ offset(LBroodSize) + SexParentFoodTreatment + SexParentArrivalTime + (1|NestNight) (family = Poisson). Use DHARMa to check residuals; comment on fit.

  2. Negative binomial GLMM. Refit with family = nbinom2. Compare AIC and DHARMa plots to the Poisson GLMM.

  3. Zero-inflation check. Use DHARMas zero-inflation test on your NB model. If indicated, add a constant zero-inflation term (ziformula = ~ 1). Does AIC improve?

  4. Model reduction. Use drop1() (LRT/AIC) to remove non-significant interactions and then non-significant main effects (one at a time). State your final model.

  5. Interpretation. Report IRRs and percent changes for FoodTreatment and ArrivalTime from your final GLMM.

  6. Compare GEE vs GLMM. Do the biological conclusions match? Briefly explain the difference between marginal (GEE) and conditional (GLMM) effects.
